73":"10 oktober 1473","Stonham Aspall, Mid Suffolk, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Stonham Aspal, Suffolk, England","of Saperton, Gloucester, Eng.":"Sapperton, Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Earl, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Woodbridge, Suffolk Coastal, Suffolk, England":"Woodbridge, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Saint Mary Church, Earl Stonham, Mid Suffolk, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Earl Stonham, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1468–1531":"1468–1531","1473–1531":"1473–1531","1492–1553":"1492–1553","1500–Male":"1500–Deceased","1446–1473":"1446–1473","1450–1550":"1450–1550","1 November 1492":"1 November 1492","1550":"1550","1473":"1473","1450":"1450","1492":"1492","abt 1500":"about 1500","1468":"1468","1446":"1446","1500":"1500","1531":"1531","1553":"1553","May 1498":"May 1498","10 October 1473":"10 October 1473","Stonham Aspall, Mid Suffolk, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Stonham Aspal, Suffolk, England","of Saperton, Gloucester, Eng.":"Sapperton, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Earl, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Woodbridge, Suffolk Coastal, Suffolk, England":"Woodbridge, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Saint Mary Church, Earl Stonham, Mid Suffolk, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Earl Stonham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Packard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>pak(e)</i> ‘pack, bundle’ + the Anglo-Norman French pejorative suffix <i>-ard</i>, probably a derogatory occupational name for a peddler.","English: pejorative derivative of the Middle English personal name   Pack  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Packert</b>, <b>Päckert</b>, from ancient Germanic personal names formed with a word meaning ‘battle’ or ‘to fight’; or a variant of   Packer   2 (with excrescent <i>-t</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Pack","meanings":["English (Kent and Devon): variant of   Pask  , derived from Middle English <i>Pake</i> ‘Easter, Passover’.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): metonymic occupational name for a wholesale trader, from Middle Low German <i>packe</i>, German <i>Pack</i> ‘bundle, package’ (see   Packer  ). Compare   Pak  .","Dutch: variant, archaic or Americanized, of   Pak  , a cognate of 2 above."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Packard II was born in 1468, in Stonham Aspal, Suffolk, England, his father, Sir Richard Packard, was 22 and his mother, Lady Katherine Stoneham, was 18. He had at least 2 sons with Margaret. He died in 1531, in his hometown, at the age of 63, and was buried in Earl Stonham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1468–1531":"1468–1531","1473–1531":"1473–1531","1492–1553":"1492–1553","1500–Male":"1500–Surnud","1446–1473":"1446–1473","1450–1550":"1450–1550","1 November 1492":"1. november 1492","1550":"1550","1473":"1473","1450":"1450","1492":"1492","abt 1500":"umbes 1500","1468":"1468","1446":"1446","1500":"1500","1531":"1531","1553":"1553","May 1498":"mai 1498","10 October 1473":"10. oktoober 1473","Stonham Aspall, Mid Suffolk, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Stonham Aspal, Suffolk, England","of Saperton, Gloucester, Eng.":"Sapperton, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Earl, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Woodbridge, Suffolk Coastal, Suffolk, England":"Woodbridge, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Saint Mary Church, Earl Stonham, Mid Suffolk, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Earl Stonham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1468–1531":"1468–1531","1473–1531":"1473–1531","1492–1553":"1492–1553","1500–Male":"1500–Kuollut","1446–1473":"1446–1473","1450–1550":"1450–1550","1 November 1492":"1. marraskuuta 1492","1550":"1550","1473":"1473","1450":"1450","1492":"1492","abt 1500":"noin 1500","1468":"1468","1446":"1446","1500":"1500","1531":"1531","1553":"1553","May 1498":"toukokuu 1498","10 October 1473":"10. lokakuuta 1473","Stonham Aspall, Mid Suffolk, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Stonham Aspal, Suffolk, England","of Saperton, Gloucester, Eng.":"Sapperton, Gloucestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Earl, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, 